1 18. "Dental laboratory technician" means an individual whose
2 name is duly filed in the official records of the Board, which
3 authorizes the technician, upon the laboratory prescription of a
4 dentist, to perform dental laboratory technology, which services
5 must be rendered only to the prescribing dentist and not to the
6 public;
7 19. "Dental laboratory technology" means using materials and
8 mechanical devices for the construction, reproduction or repair of
9 dental restorations, appliances or other devices to be worn in a
10 human mouth;
11 20. "Dental specialty" means a specialized practice of a branch
12 of dentistry, recognized by the Board, where the dental college and
13 specialty program are accredited by the Commission on Dental
14 Accreditation (CODA), or a dental specialty recognized by the Board,
15 requiring a minimum number of hours of approved education and
16 training and/or recognition by a nationally recognized association
17 or accreditation board;
18 21. "Direct supervision" means the supervisory dentist is in
19 the dental office or treatment facility and, during the appointment,
20 personally examines the patient, diagnoses any conditions to be
21 treated, and authorizes the procedures to be performed by a dental
22 hygienist or dental assistant. The supervising dentist is
23 continuously on-site and physically present in the dental office or
24 treatment facility while the procedures are being performed and,
Req. No. 16791 Page 6

1 befo re dismissal of the patient, evaluates the results of the dental
2 treatment;
3 22. "Direct visual supervision" means the supervisory dentist
4 has direct ongoing visual oversight which shall be maintained at all
5 times during any procedure authorized to be performed by a dental
6 assistant;
7 23. "Expanded duty" means a dental procedure for which a dental
8 assistant has received special training in a course of study
9 approved by the Board;
10 24. "Fellowship" means a program designed for post-residency
11 graduates to gain knowledge and experience in a specialized field;
12 25. "General anesthesia" means a drug-induced loss of
13 consciousness during which patients are not arousable, even by
14 painful stimulation. The ability to independently maintain
15 ventilator function is often impaired. Patients often require
16 assistance in maintaining a patent airway, and positive pressure
17 ventilation may be required because of depressed spontaneous
18 ventilation or drug-induced depression of neuromuscular function.
19 Cardiovascular function may be impaired;
20 26. "General supervision" means the supervisory dentist has
21 diagnosed any conditions to be treated within the past thirteen (13)
22 months, has personally authorized the procedures to be performed by
23 a dental hygienist, and will evaluate the results of the dental
24 treatment within a reasonable time as determined by the nature of
