13 administration of nitrous oxide, therapeutic use of lasers and
14 administration of local anesthesia, may be performed under general
15 supervision and neuromodulator administration, therapeutic use of
16 lasers, and phlebotomy and venipuncture shall be performed only
17 under the direct or indirect supervision of a dentist. The level of
18 supervision, whether direct, indirect, or general, for the advanced
19 procedure of elder care and public health pursuant to Section 7 of
20 this act shall be at the discretion of the supervisory dentist.
21 Authorization for general supervision shall be limited to a maximum
22 of thirteen (13) months following an examination by the supervisory
23 dentist of a patient of record.
24
Req. No. 16791 Page 46

1 C. 1. A dentist may authorize procedures to be performed by a
2 dental hygienist, without complying with the provisions of paragraph
3 3 of subsection B of this section, if:
4 a. the dental hygienist has at least two (2) years'
5 experience in the practice of dental hygiene,
6 b. the authorization to perform the procedures is in
7 writing and signed by the dentist, and
8 c. the procedures are performed during an initial visit
9 to a person in a treatment facility, or pursuant to
10 Section 7 of this act.
11 2. The person upon whom the procedures are performed must be
12 referred to a dentist after completion of the procedures performed
13 pursuant to paragraph 1 of this subsection.
14 3. A dental hygienist shall not perform a second set of
15 procedures on a person pursuant to this subsection until the person
16 has been examined and accepted for dental care by a dentist.
17 4. The treatment facility in which any procedure is performed
18 by a dental hygienist pursuant to this subsection shall note each
19 such procedure in the medical records of the person upon whom the
20 procedure was performed and list the dentist that authorized the
21 hygienist to perform the procedures signed by the hygienist.
22 D. A treatment facility may employ dental hygienists whose
23 services shall be limited to the examination of teeth and the
24 teaching of dental hygiene or as otherwise authorized by the Board.
Req. No. 16791 Page 47

1 E. The Board is authorized to prescribe, by rule, the
2 educational requirements for advanced procedures that may be
3 performed by a dental hygienist upon receipt of the advanced
4 procedures designated on his or her license. The advanced
5 procedures shall include the administration of local anesthesia, the
6 administration of nitrous oxide analgesia, neuromodulator
7 administration, therapeutic use of lasers, phlebotomy and
8 venipuncture, and elder care and public health pursuant to Section 7
9 of this act.
10 F. A dental hygienist shall not own or operate an independent
11 practice of dental hygiene.
12 G. Nothing in the State Dental Act shall be construed to
13 prohibit a dentist from performing any of the procedures that may be
14 performed by a dental hygienist.
15 H. Nothing in the State Dental Act shall be construed to allow
16 a dental assistant to work under the supervision of a dental
17 hygienist while acting under direct, indirect or general
18 supervision, except as provided by Section 7 328.24(I) and Section
19 328.57 of this act title.
20 SECTION 13. AMENDATORY 59 O.S. 2021, Section 328.54, is
21 amended to read as follows:
22 Section 328.54. A. Any person conducting a diagnosis for the
23 purpose of prescribing medication or treatment or any other action
24 determined to be a dental practice as defined by the State Dental
Req. No. 16791 Page 48

1 Act, via the Internet or other telecommunications device on any
2 patient that is physically located in this state shall hold a valid
3 Oklahoma state dental license.
4 B. A "patient of record" may be established by teledentistry
5 for the purposes of an emergency or hygiene treatment if the patient
6 is physically located at the dental office or treatment facility and
7 the dentist is not readily available.
8 B. A dentist holding a valid dental license in Oklahoma may
9 consult, diagnose and treat a patient of record via synchronous or
10 asynchronous telecommunication between the patient and dentist. The
11 dentist must record all activities relating to teledentistry in the
12 patient record and must have an office location in Oklahoma
13 available for follow-up treatment and maintenance of records.
14 SECTION 14. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
15 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 328.21(a) of Title 59, unless
16 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
17 A. A dentist, having received a dental degree or certificate in
18 a foreign country that is a non-United states or Canadian accredited
19 program, may apply for a dental hygiene license upon meeting the
20 following requirements:
21 1. The applicant must provide proof of a valid dental education
22 and degree, certificate or other proof of acceptable by the Board
23 and proof of lawful practice of dentistry for the past two years in
24
Req. No. 16791 Page 49

1 a fo reign country. All documents shall be translated to English and
2 verifiable by the Board;
3 2. Successful passage of the ADEX dental hygiene licensure
4 exam;
5 3. Successful passage of the Test of English as a Foreign
6 Language (TOEFL). The Applicant can provide proof of passing the
7 TOEFL exam within the past five (5) years;
8 4. Successful completion of an evaluation program to practice
9 dental hygiene conducted by the University of Oklahoma College of
10 Dentistry;
11 5. Successful completion of the Oklahoma Jurisprudence exam.
12 SECTION 15. This act shall become effective November 1, 2026.
